column21: These are D-Ala-D-Ala ligases, they bind two alanines in distinct pockets. So there is a K1 and a K2, both for alanine, and then a Km for ATP. DdlA (kcat 444/min, K1 5.7 uM, K2 0.55 mM, Km ATP 38 uM) can also bind D-aminobutyrate (kcat = 1.09 * kcat for alanine, K1 0.12 mM, K2 8.9 mM), glycine (kcat = 0.63 * kcat for alanine, K1 2.3 mM, K2 79 mM). D-Ala-D-Ala is a non-competitive inhibitor (Ki 49 uM); D-cycloserine is a competitive inhibitor (Ki 8.9 uM); aminoalkyl phosphinate inhibitor is also competitive (Ki 130 uM, k_inact [not sure what this is] 2.4/min). The equation they use is vmax * S^2/(K1 K2 + K2 S + S^2) which means they are dropping K1 S for some reason.
